Looking forward to hearing from you.   Kind regards,  Petra Nahlikova

- Help with upcoming 2021/22 self-assessment tax

If you are able to help and take on my case, please can you let me know the price of your services and a rough estimate of how much you think it would be to resolve a case like this.

Kind regards,
Madeleine"

Description:
"Good day!

I am currently trying to look for options within EU for full-time relocation, hopefully finding a place which fits my desired lifestyle and provides good tax environment for my investments.

I found you on the internet, and wanted to reach out to you as my possible partner for relocation to:

Portugal / or other EU country that has good enviroment for my situation


My main source of income comes from investing in cryptocurrencies, let me describe exactly what I am doing:

My main investments are all about NFTs ( non-fungible-tokens) assets.
Let me put this on concrete example of Axie Infinity game. (link to whitepaper https://whitepaper.axieinfinity.com/ )

Axie Infinity is a game where you can play with exactly 3 NFTs called "Axies".
For playing the game with them you earn cryptocurrencies such as SLP and AXS.
Axies can also be breed together and in the process create new Axies (new NFTs), for a certain amount of SLP and AXS.

What I am doing in these games is the following:
Breeding (creating) new NFTs and selling them on marketplace for immediate profit. ( in Axie case, its sold in ETH - link to marketplace https://marketplace.axieinfinity.com/axie/ )
Keeping the NFTs and "renting" them to players who play the game for me, and we split the profits according to a deal we have with each player. For example, player earns 6000 SLP in a month, and we split that 50/50 -> so 3000 SLP for me and 3000 SLP for him.
Third thing we do is we buy underpriced Axies from the marketplace and sell them for profit (at the correct market price).

This whole "genre" in NFT & Gaming is called "play to earn" or P2E for short. My business is finding & investing into these games, and profit on them in all of the 3 ways described above.

I also buy & hold other cryptocurrencies, and also sporadically "buy low, sell high" cryptocurrencies. Sometimes in span of few hours or days. I use both CEX and DEX to exchange cryptocurrencies (from DEX I use binance/kraken/crypto.com currently)
I also stake cryptocurrencies and earn rewards that way. (for example AXS https://stake.axieinfinity.com/ )
I also dabble in decentalized finance (de-fi) and providing Liquidity into Liquidity pools.
I also partake in twitter giveaways for NFTs etc.



Some more background info that could be important:

I have Czech Republic Passport
Dependants -> I dont have kids or wife, but I do have girlfriend that would relocate wtih me. She has Czech Republic Passport too. She is not involved in the business (but can be via administrative work)
I currently have only one side source of income:
I rent an agriculture property in Czech republic, where I get like 120 eur per year for it.
No other source of incomes for the time being.
I have bank accounts only open In CZ + Revolut.
Up until now I am doing these investments based from Czech Republic, im not sure how would taxing this year go, if I relocated before reaching 1/2 of tax year as resident in Czech Republic.


I want to ask if this is something that you can help me with, or if you could point me in the direciton of someone who can.

I am preferably looking for partners who could help me with everything related to relocation.


Thank you for your time reading this.


Best regards,
Kamil Karásek"

"Hi there,

We are in the process of moving to Portugal from the UK (we have been granted the D7 retiree visa based on passive income although we are not retiring and are continuing to work).

We have a UK limited company (this is an online business and both myself and my wife work for the company and are the only 2 shareholders) and have been advised by our UK accountant that we should have non domiciled UK tax status and continue to pay standard tax in the UK (both for our company and personal tax).

- If there is anything we need to do before leaving the UK and our residency officially commencing in Portugal (we are due to arrive in Portugal first week of April with our follow up appointment with the SEF in May)
- Any impact to our Limited company and us as the shareholders of the company
- Any impact on us as managers receiving a salary from the company
- Any impact on our UK property (we own one which we rent out)
- CGT considerations on our investments (ISA, SIPP, company investments and crypto investments)

Please confirm if you offer a consultation call to advise on the above and clarity on fees.

Many thanks

Paul Shulver"

Last Action: Email - RHJ Accountants Newsletter: June 2023 (Joanna Staniforth-Burch)
Description:
"Dear rhj accountants team,

My name is Robert Gray. I am a British citizen and I have lived and worked in the UK my whole life (as an academic at various universities) except for a 3-year period 2010-2012 when I worked at the University of Lisbon in Portugal.

When I worked in Portugal I obtained a NIF and I paid taxes in Portugal on my income for the years I was there.

Then I returned to the UK at the end of 2012, and I have been living, working and paying tax in the UK (at the University of East Anglia in Norwich) since then.

I currently have no income, no property, and no bank accounts in Portugal.

Around 6 months ago I found out that when I left Portugal I was meant to fill out a change of address form to notify the Portuguese financas that I had left the country. But I did not fill out that form, and so according to their records I am still living in my old address in Portugal from 10 years ago!

When I left Portugal I thought that since I would no longer be submitting any tax returns in Portugal (since I no longer worked or lived there) then there would be no problems. But for some reason (still not explained to me) in 2017 the Portuguese financas team decided to submit a tax return on my behalf (automatically) which involved them contacting HMRC to find out how much I earned in the UK that year. And now the Portuguese want me to pay tax on my UK income from 2017 in Portugal since they claim I was resident in Portugal that year (which I was not). Of course I already paid tax on all my UK income for 2017 in the UK (since I was resident here), and similarly for every other year since I have been back. And I have all the paperwork to prove this including copies of all of my P60 forms between 2013 and now.

Since finding out about this I have been communicating with various people in the Portuguese financas to try and get it resolved.

According to their instructions the main thing I think I need to try and get done is to get them to agree to the fact that I have been resident in the UK since the end of 2012, and for this I have been trying unsuccessfully to complete and submit a form called "Model A - REQUEST FOR CHANGE OF ADDRESS WITH RETROACTIVE EFFECTS".

Getting this form submitted and accepted seems to be more difficult than I had first anticipated. It seems to involve:
(1) Translating lots of documents relating to proof of address in the last 10 years into Portuguese, and also
(2) I have been told that I also need a Fiscal Representative in order to complete the form (I think because of Brexit).

Ultimately my goals are to:
(a) Get them to update their records to reflect the fact that I have been living in the UK since the end of 2012.

(b) Due to (a), that they annul their claim that I owe them tax for the year 2017 since I was resident and a taxpayer in the UK that year (and every year since 2013 to present), and ideally

(c) Since I no longer have any connection with Portugal (no property, bank accounts, or income) I do not want to have a NIF since I do not need one. I don't know if it is possible to cancel ones NIF after leaving the country?

Do you think that you might be able to offer me any advice or assistance in getting this sorted out?

Thanks, kind regards,

Robert D. Gray
50 Blakestone Drive
Norwich, Norfolk, UK
NR7 0LF"

Description:
"Hello,

I am writing to you in search of advice regarding how my UK LTD company will be treated tax wise were I to move and become resident of Portugal as my current UK accountant didn't feel they had enough knowledge on the matter to help.

The LTD has only one director currently, which is myself. I was using it to receive royalties and distribute profits via dividends/salary/pension and any excess profits were invested in passive global tracking index funds via Vanguard to be drawn down at a future date, the funds are Irish and UK domiciled UCITS. No active trading would take place once resident of Portugal, although the funds pay out dividends twice per year.

Once I become a Portuguese tax resident these royalties will be received by myself personally as according to advice I received they should be tax exempt under the Portuguese NHR regime. I assume once the LTD stops receiving active income and becomes an entity that holds purely passive investment vehicles that it will be classified as a closed investment company.

As I understand it once I am resident of Portugal then the company will fall under the permanent establishment rules laid out in the DTA as the effective place of management will be Portugal and thus liable to Portuguese corporation tax. Also from what I saw there may be a possibility that shifting of company residence will create an exit charge on any unrealised gains made by the company as none of the investments are in immovable property.

I hope you will be able to assist me with this matter and thanks in advance for any information.

Kind regards,

James."

Email - RHJ Accountants Newsletter: June 2023 (Joanna Staniforth-Burch)
Description: Hello Filipe and Raquel,    My name is Monica, and I got your contact from José Rey, one of your clients.    I am writing to ask you for some advice on my current tax situation, related to my new job, and see if we can eventually start a new long-term collaboration. My situation is very similar to José's, and below are more details:   I am Italian, but resident in Portugal for almost three years. Two weeks ago I have started working as an independent contractor, for a company located in Gibraltar, UK. I have already submitted my Declaração de Inicio de Atividade in Portal das Finanças (sending it attached).  The company is a Marketing Agency, and I will specifically provide digital advertising services to them. I will work remotely from Portugal, at my Fiscal Residence address.    From a recent conversation with another accountant, I got this info about taxes: IRS: It will be calculated on the 75% of my annual income, for a rate of 25%. To be declared within April 2024. VAT: I will need to declare it every three months, but I am not subject to its payment as I am providing a service to a company outside the EU.  Segurança Social: I will start paying it in 2024, after this first year of activity (I have no more info on that). Can you confirm I understood the three points correctly?    As we're close to the end of the month, I tried to simulate the issue of an invoice, and I got two doubts: - Regarding IRS: there is no 75% base option.  - Regarding VAT: I am not sure if I need to select one of the Isenção or Regime Normal.   Other than the Invoices, I'd like to ask you how it would work in terms of processes and costs if you could take care of my accounts in general, including declarations, etc.    Thank you very much for your help, and I remain available in case you need any additional info.    Have a nice weekend,    Monica Saba

Description: My wife and I have moved to Portugal. I am a British citizen with a Portuguese residence card and my wife is a Portuguese citizen with settled status in the UK. We are both UK taxpayers, employed by UK companies, but the pandemic shifted our lifestyle and we spend most of our time in Portugal at the moment, but we consider ourselves as living in both countries.  I believe I met the criteria for UK tax residency in 2021-2022 and I will be filing my tax return for that year as such, but I am now in a grey area for this year. We have purchased property in Portugal so I think we are now automatically non-resident for the 2022-2023 year despite retaining a UK property as well. I don't think the 'ties' test helps me there but I struggle to follow any of the flowcharts I have found to determine our tax residency. If you are working for a UK company, just remotely from your home in a foreign country, does that count as UK work or not?  I am uncertain how being non-UK resident will affect my filing a tax return in January 2024 but I think I have read that non UK-residents can't file online via the HMRC web interface and have to use a tax software package instead. Is this the case?  What are the other implications of not being UK tax resident while still being employed and paid by a UK company?  My wife has never had to file a tax return, always being covered by PAYE, so what will have to change for her?  We would also like to get advice on Portugal's NHR (non-habitual residence) program. If we can be accepted for that, it might make things easier for us tax-wise but there is a question about capital gains tax. I hold a significant amount of shares in the group of companies that I am employed by. My understanding is that capital gains is paid in the country of residence and that Portugal charges a higher rate on capital gains. I do receive some dividends from these shares, although not a significant sum at the moment. I understand that NHR might lead to savings there but I have tried to understand where I would pay tax on those and how much, and I don't understand.  Most advice I read seems to discuss cases where people move to or from the UK and stay there. We are going to be in Portugal for the time being but as our young son gets older, we'll have to choose which country we want to educate him in and we'll settle in that one. I have read about 'temporary non-residence' and wonder if there is anything there I should worry about should we return to UK residence in less than 5 years for our son's education.  Are you able to advise us on these matters?  16.9.2022 Nicole sent an initial enquiry form and also a link for them to book a meeting with Filipe and Jeremiah  23.9.2022 Nicole sent another email checking if they still wanted a meeting and resent the enquiry form  23.9.22 Nicole sent another link for him to book in with J and F  23.9.22 Tristan filled out the enquiry form and also booked his meeting for Wednesday 28th  28.9.22 Tristans meeting went ahead but Jeremiah was not there and he was needed, so Nicole sent out a link for him to book in again

Description: Referral from Hannah Aylett -   Hi there,   I received your recommendation from Hannah May, I hope you don't mind me reaching out directly.  I am looking for a tax lawyer to help me obtain the NHR status and potentially help issue my tax return. I have quite an international background/case so I am hoping you would be able to offer me some advice and guidance.   I have done extensive research into the NHR process and know that I am eligible, and understand that having moved to Portugal within the next year I will need to apply for this by the March deadline this year.   I have been speaking with another lawyer, however am not satisfied with the service, therefore urgently looking for another solution.   A bit about myself:  I am a Belgian citizen with an EU passport (actually I'm a dual citizen, I hold both a Belgian and Thai passport) I moved to Portugal during the summer of 2022. I obtained the NIF in July 2022 and signed a lease agreement in August 2022.  Before this, I was living briefly in Thailand (and was able to stay there without a visa, due to my Thai citizenship) during the Pandemic. I moved my domicile to the Belgian embassy in Bangkok, Thailand in 2021, and have not moved it from there since.  Before that, I lived and worked in London, UK for several years (before Brexit) where I was paying taxes and domiciled at the Belgian embassy in London.  I am self-employed and own a business that is incorporated and based in Estonia. I pay corporate tax in Estonia and pay myself a salary, for which I am responsible to declare my personal income tax in my country of residence. I have not yet declared a tax return for my personal income in 2022. As I am a new 'resident' to Portugal, I would like to make this my tax residency under the NHR program.  Beside the NIF, I do not believe I am 'officially' registered as a resident in Portugal yet - though I am not sure if this is necessary beyond the NIF? Is this needed to move forward with the NHR status? In terms of documentation, I can offer you my NIF application, lease agreement, utility bills, and phone contract.  Please let me know if you are able to help me and offer me a quote. I am happy to arrange a call. You can contact me directly at +351910053720.  Many thanks,  Lisa

Description: Hello.  me and my brother moved to Portugal in november last year, and we are looking into starting our own companies.  We come from Denmark, and there we had what is called a "single person company", it is basically just that you get a company/vat number, and can do business, but it is not a separate entity, by definition all profits becomes your own salary, and there is no limited liability or anything like that, and there is no company constitution or shares or anything like that.  We have researched a little bit, and from what we can see there are several forms of companies possible in Portugal, something called "freelancer", "sole trader" and some personal limited(lda) or limited liability with 2 or more partners.   We would like to hear about our options, and if possible we can pay you to help us register the company type best fitting to us.  We would prefer something as close to what we have in Denmark, unless there are huge negatives. Being limited liability is not important to us, as we have some very specific b2b customers, so it will not be a problem. What matters to us is the complexity in maintaining the company, and other downsides/benefits we may not know about already. We have heard something about freelancers/sole traders getting discount on social security fee first year for example, but these are things we need guidance on.  I hope you can help us, Thanks

Description: Like Jocelyn, I work at Cloudflare. I started in California in 2017, and I am still registered to vote there. I moved to Portugal at the end of 2020, and I am currently on a Portuguese employment contract. I pay into Portuguese social security.   My compensation is a mixture of salary and stock.   The salary has Portuguese income tax withheld from it, but I also receive a "settling-in allowance" which I believe does not have tax withheld. The two components combined total about 131,000 EUR annually, before taxes.   The stock compensation comes in the form of Restricted Stock Units, and participation in an Employee Stock Purchase Plan. The RSUs this year probably totaled around 200,000 USD in fair market value, and I automatically sold shares to cover taxes in the US (despite the shares vesting in Portugal). The ESPP shares I bought at a discount.   In addition to the RSU releases and ESPP purchases, I:   - sold more RSUs and ESPP shares - exercised-and-held previously-vested Incentive Stock Options - rebalanced my ordinary (non-Cloudflare) stock portfolio, which included selling stock and put options - contributed to a traditional IRA, then converted that contribution to a Roth IRA   In Portugal, I benefit from the Non-Habitual Resident tax regime, which means I pay a 20% flat tax rate on income here.   I believe that sums up the main interesting bits.   For the past two years, Cloudflare paid a firm called Vialto Partners to do my taxes for me. Beginning this year, I am on my own, which leads me to you.   Specifically, I could use help preparing and filing tax returns in both countries -- and probably California, too.
